01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:24.399
back to me that's different, depending on what I posted. Sometimes there are endpoints that are

01:08:24.399 --> 01:08:29.359
get endpoints, where you just say, hey, hey, and then it will give you something. There's,

01:08:29.359 --> 01:08:33.759
you know, more complex things involved here, like query parameters, where you can say to that

01:08:33.759 --> 01:08:39.759
service, I actually want my query to be slightly like this, you know, and you can change things

01:08:39.759 --> 01:08:46.479
via query parameters. But I think the most important thing to think about a REST or RESTful

01:08:46.479 --> 01:08:59.759
API is that it is a way to set up a service that can interact via HTTP calls to other computers,

01:08:59.759 --> 01:09:05.680
say, like your local computer or another part of your IT infrastructure. So, the RStudio Pro

01:09:05.680 --> 01:09:12.160
product that supports deploying APIs in Python or R is RStudio Connect. So, Connect can be used

01:09:12.160 --> 01:09:21.200
to deploy Python APIs, like via FastAPI, Flask, that ever builds on top of FastAPI, and in the

01:09:21.200 --> 01:09:28.399
R side, Plumber APIs. Do you want to add anything to that, Isabel? That was a very fuzzy, non-technical

01:09:28.399 --> 01:09:34.959
definition of what a REST API is. No, I think that was a great start. It really

01:09:34.959 --> 01:09:42.959
is just a way to, like, for people or machines to connect applications, whatever an application is,

01:09:44.160 --> 01:09:50.879
which is another whole discussion, but to connect these together in some sort of standardized way,

01:09:50.879 --> 01:09:56.080
which is through the open API specifications, which you don't need to know anything about if

01:09:56.080 --> 01:10:02.479
you're just learning about REST APIs. I wouldn't jump off that diving board quite yet.

