01:13:02.799 --> 01:13:08.399
but it was a question on YouTube. Do you need to make a Dockerfile if you're deploying to Connect?

01:13:09.359 --> 01:13:16.240
Nope. Just the one-liner will get you on the Python or R side from your local environment

01:13:16.240 --> 01:13:24.479
to Connect. Awesome. Thank you. Another anonymous question was, for model monitoring,

01:13:24.479 --> 01:13:30.399
can you define custom metrics instead of predefined metrics? So, I'll answer this for

01:13:30.399 --> 01:13:34.319
the R side, and then, Isabella, you can answer it for the Python side. So, yes. So, the way to do

01:13:34.319 --> 01:13:44.640
that on the R side is to create a yardstick metric. So, custom metrics in yardstick involve

01:13:44.640 --> 01:13:50.080
writing a function and then calling the wrapper, and then, all the infrastructure will know,

01:13:50.080 --> 01:13:55.040
ah, this is a metric that I need to aggregate at the same interval that I'm doing all the

01:13:55.040 --> 01:14:00.399
other metrics. So, I actually have a blog post about how to write a yardstick custom metric.

01:14:01.359 --> 01:14:07.600
You can take a look for that. It's just like writing a little function and wrapping it in this

01:14:08.399 --> 01:14:12.959
wrapper. So, it's not too straightforward. And we know, you know, we know people who like

01:14:14.640 --> 01:14:19.839
that ability to extend with custom metrics is important in many organizations because you want

01:14:19.839 --> 01:14:26.080
to actually, say, have a metric that has specific, you know, business logic in it or something like

01:14:26.080 --> 01:14:31.439
that, and you want to be able to optimize and or monitor with that directly. Isabella, you want to

01:14:31.439 --> 01:14:37.600
talk about it for Python? Yeah. On the Python side, you can write any function as long as it has a,

01:14:38.240 --> 01:14:44.799
like, a why true column. So, the truth and a predicted value. It will compare those to the

01:14:45.439 --> 01:14:51.439
whatever metric you are creating and return back the value. So, you are able to use custom

01:14:51.439 --> 01:15:00.399
metrics there as well. Awesome. Another question. Can we deploy a Shiny app with Vetiver?

