01:15:55.520 --> 01:16:03.520
One says – okay. Anonymous question that just came in. Most of our models have an ID

01:16:03.520 --> 01:16:08.160
in the recipe step, which seems to fail in predictions. With Vetiver,

01:16:08.160 --> 01:16:11.520
is it best to remove non-predictor ID columns?

01:16:13.520 --> 01:16:18.879
So, there have been some updates. So, this person is using tidy models with recipes,

01:16:18.879 --> 01:16:26.959
and they have something in their input that is not a predictor that they keep around,

01:16:26.959 --> 01:16:37.120
maybe for diagnosing problems or analyzing results. It's something you don't want to

01:16:37.120 --> 01:16:42.959
use for prediction, but that you want to have and keep in the datasets. So,

01:16:42.959 --> 01:16:50.479
I think there's a couple ways you approach this. One is you require it for the input.

01:16:50.479 --> 01:16:58.959
You say, I actually want – when this model is in production, I want that ID,

01:16:59.520 --> 01:17:03.279
and I'm going to record it and use it for monitoring or something like that.

01:17:03.279 --> 01:17:13.200
So, then you make a – I think that is what will work by default. The other option is you,

01:17:14.160 --> 01:17:19.279
when you go to train a final model, like, say, in the tidy model sense, you've done lots of

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:26.160
tuning, and then it's time to do last fits. You take the ID out, and you retrain it at that point.

01:17:26.160 --> 01:17:29.759
You train it, not retrain it. Train it without the ID, because you're not going to use it

01:17:29.759 --> 01:17:39.200
in production. The other option is to pass in custom input data prototype. And so, here,

01:17:39.839 --> 01:17:46.720
when you create that Vetiver deployable model object, there's a number of optional arguments.

01:17:46.720 --> 01:17:54.479
One of them is, hey, what is the input data prototype that I'm going to check against?

01:17:54.479 --> 01:18:05.120
And you can go into your workflow and pull out the mold and just get the predictors,

01:18:05.120 --> 01:18:12.560
and then pass that in, and then that is another way. So, the default behavior,

01:18:12.560 --> 01:18:16.799
it kind of assumes you have predictors. You're going to end up with a prediction.

01:18:17.520 --> 01:18:21.680
But if you have a slightly more complex use case, there's these different ways,

01:18:21.680 --> 01:18:23.919
and you can choose what works best for you.

01:18:27.040 --> 01:18:32.000
Okay. Two more questions, and then I will let you go. Thank you so much for answering all these.

01:18:33.040 --> 01:18:38.720
One from Javier on YouTube was, can you please confirm if the performance metrics are customizable

01:18:39.520 --> 01:18:43.040
for the metrics that were displayed on the Vetiver HTML export?

01:18:44.479 --> 01:18:51.120
Yes. So, on the R side, it is one of the arguments to the compute metrics. The default

01:18:51.120 --> 01:18:57.680
is to use a default set of metrics, but you can use – you know, you can change it. You can

01:18:57.680 --> 01:19:01.359
write your own custom metrics function. So, it is one of the arguments that goes in there,

01:19:01.359 --> 01:19:05.919
is you need a metric set function. So, on the – I think we already said this,

01:19:05.919 --> 01:19:10.799
but maybe, Isabel, just to confirm. Yep. On the Python side, it also is

01:19:10.799 --> 01:19:17.040
called metric set, and then you'll pass in a list of – I normally do scikit-learn metrics,

01:19:17.040 --> 01:19:20.799
but again, if it has the Y true and Y predicted columns,

01:19:20.799 --> 01:19:25.120
that is what this function is using to make your metric output.

01:19:28.560 --> 01:19:32.640
