01:19:33.520 --> 01:19:37.439
is Vetiver for Python as complete as it is for R?

01:19:38.799 --> 01:19:40.640
That's a great question. Do you want to start, Isabel?

01:19:41.279 --> 01:19:48.399
Yeah, of course. So, I would say it is pretty darn close. We don't – so, we think – the

01:19:48.399 --> 01:19:55.680
Python side does not have the template for the dashboard yet, but I think everything you saw

01:19:55.680 --> 01:20:04.080
today was kind of feature parity between the two languages. I don't think we expect to, like,

01:20:04.720 --> 01:20:09.839
be super strict with everything that's in R is in Python, because these two demographics have

01:20:09.839 --> 01:20:18.399
different needs, but we're going to kind of see where the community takes us, I guess, and see

01:20:18.399 --> 01:20:24.240
what people are using and really want to help them with their MLOps workflows in each language,

01:20:24.240 --> 01:20:28.879
respectively. Yeah, I think that's right on. I mean, I think if you're talking about, like,

01:20:28.879 --> 01:20:33.919
is coverage as complete, I think probably so. Like, depending on – like, if you were going

01:20:33.919 --> 01:20:40.080
to ask what do people want to use in Python, like, the coverage is about as complete in Python as

01:20:40.080 --> 01:20:48.640
R. Everything we showed you today, the coverage is about as complete. There are some things that,

01:20:48.640 --> 01:20:56.240
because the existing machine learning infrastructure is different, you know, in the two – like,

01:20:56.240 --> 01:21:00.319
the model development infrastructure is a little different, that things do end up slightly

01:21:00.319 --> 01:21:10.720
different. And we don't – we want these to feel consistent and to make – and, like, that someone

01:21:10.720 --> 01:21:17.439
who is – wants to collaborate with you as a model developer, it basically is consistent, like,

01:21:17.439 --> 01:21:22.560
what you're doing in one side versus the other. But we also want these to feel native. Like,

01:21:22.560 --> 01:21:28.479
if you are some – we don't want, like, a high goal – like, a high priority, actually, for us is that

01:21:28.479 --> 01:21:32.799
the Python implementation, the implementation, someone doesn't come to it and is like,

01:21:33.600 --> 01:21:38.000
why does this look like I'm writing R code? Like, we do not want that to be the feeling

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:42.959
that anyone has on either side, right? So, we want it to be very native feeling on both sides.

